    <scopecontent>
      <head>Scope and Content</head>
      <p>This collection consists of ca. 3,000 items, (13 Hollingers
         and 15 oversize bound volumes), ca. 9 linear shelf feet), ca.
         1907-1949, chiefly the genealogical correspondence and
         research of 
         <persname>William D. Ligon, Jr.</persname>concerning the 
         <famname>Ligon family</famname>. The collection contains
         correspondence, newsclippings, photographs, post cards,
         photostats, forms, genealogical charts, book reviews,
         Christmas card albums, and printed material, much of it
         mounted in bound volumes and scrapbooks. Also present is the
         typescript and illustrations for the book 
         <title xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" xlink:type="simple" render="italic" xlink:href="">The Ligon Family and
         Connections,</title>the product of all of the research and
         genealogical inquiries conducted by Ligon through his
         correspondence.</p>
      <p>Much of the information concerns the first and second 
         <famname>Ligon</famname>reunions, in 
         <geogname>Richmond, Virginia</geogname>, and 
         <geogname>Washington, D.C.</geogname>respectively, 
         <persname>William D. Ligon</persname>'s visit to 
         <geogname>England</geogname>in 1938, and the 
         <famname>Ligon</famname>kin in 
         <geogname>England</geogname>, especially the Royal Family. A
         copy of the two volume published work can be found in the Rare
         Books Division (see CS 71. L724 1947). According to 
         <persname>Ligon</persname>, the founder of the family in 
         <geogname>Virginia</geogname>, was Colonel 
         <persname>Thomas Ligon</persname><persname>[Lygon]</persname>who came to 
         <geogname>Henrico County, Virginia</geogname>, in 1641. 
         <persname>Thomas Ligon</persname>married 
         <persname>Mary Harris</persname>, daughter of Captain 
         <persname>Thomas Harris</persname>, who arrived in 
         <geogname>Virginia</geogname>in 1611 from 
         <geogname>Essex, England</geogname>. Other related families
         include: 
         <famname>Beauchamp</famname>, 
         <famname>Berkeley</famname>, 
         <famname>Corbin</famname>, 
         <famname>Harris</famname>, and 
         <famname>Savage</famname>.</p>
    </scopecontent>
